<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1952,2015]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,153,467]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="202" pageId="6" pageNumber="201">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Heinrich" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[151,405,1952,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Cagiva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cephalanthana">
<emphasis box="[151,405,1952,1979]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="201">Cagiva cephalanthana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small (forewing length 4.0–4.7), rather dark species with a white to cream colored head, described from a series of specimens from Lake Charlotte, Texas. The forewing pattern is ill-defined, somewhat irregularly checkered with copper, pink, and reddish brown, with a darker brown to black median fascia (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1406,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1832,1857]" captionTargetBox="[194,1394,166,1812]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[192,1396,166,1812]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Adults of Cochylini genera. 1. Anacochylidia maderana, Madera Canyon, Santa Rita Mountains, Arizona (EME). 2. Cagiva cephalanthana, Dorman Lake, Oktibbeha Co., Mississippi (USNM). 3. Atroposia oenotherana, Houston, Harris Co., Texas (USNM). 4. Atroposia oenotherana, Radisson, Onondaga Co., New York (USNM). 5. Cybilla hubbardana, Shafter, Presidio Co., Texas (USNM). 6. Cybilla hubbardana, Lordsburg, Hidalgo Co., New Mexico (CNC). 7. Honca grandis, Chimney Gulch, Golden, Colorado (USNM). 8. Pogospinia floridana, Long Key State Park, Monroe Co., Florida (USNM). 9. Nycthia pimama, Portal, Cochise Co., Arizona (USNM). 10. Nycthia yuccatana, Falcon State Park, Starr Co., Texas (USNM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442348/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="202">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). I have examined specimens from Texas (USNM), Oklahoma (BDGU), Missouri (USNM), Indiana (MSC), Maryland (MSC), Rhode Island (MSC), and Mississippi (USNM). Specimens from Texas and Mississippi were reared from the seed pods of button-bush, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rehder" authorityYear="1949" baseAuthorityName="André" box="[483,780,261,287]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Cephalanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="7" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis box="[483,780,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="202">Cephalanthus occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[825,949,261,288]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="7" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rubiaceae</taxonomicName>
). The specimens from Mississippi were collected as larvae in August and emerged in September; the specimens from Texas were collected as larvae in early September and emerged in late September and October. Field-collected adults were taken in July and August. It is assumed that there are two broods annually, with adults in July‒August and September‒October.
</paragraph>
